  (Principle
    "Intent query surface defaults to summary-first. Verbatim, context, and timestamp are noise for routine querying; available on demand for verification and provenance. The cheap shape is the default; expensive provenance is requested explicitly."
    "any agent reading [the intent file] is going to get a lot of noise. Like the timestamps isn't always useful. … most of the time just the summary is enough."
    "Settling spirit's query surface design: IntentRecordObservation returns summary only by default; verbatim-on-demand variants exist for provenance queries."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T15:30:00Z)

  (Decision
    "Intent records have a richer lifecycle than binary supersession. Three transitions: (1) full negation — prior is invalidated, archived, GC-eligible after retention; (2) certainty lowering — prior stays but confidence drops without full negation; (3) escalation on partial contradiction — when the agent can't decide between negation and co-existence, escalate to the psyche or to a review agent. Spirit (or a spirit-guardian sub-actor) chooses among the three."
    "Maybe there's like another certainty variant, which is negated … this could eventually lead to garbage collection where the negated components are garbage collected and potentially put into an archive. … Or it could say, yeah, both are actually still valid, but this preceding one is like now less certain because they don't completely overlap. … the agent is not sure … then he brings about an escalation."
    "Extending today's binary supersession protocol with negation / lowering / escalation transitions. The 'spirit guardian' lives as a sub-actor in spirit's tree."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T15:30:00Z)

  (Principle
